<paragraph id="1A1E1A5DFF97FF86B68BFC05A6B7FB74" blockId="1.[174,1233,977,1324]" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">
Diagnosis. This species is characterized by the irregularly granulate metasoma (as on 
<figureCitation id="829A06D8FF97FF86B6C6FC25A492FBD4" box="[174,231,1009,1036]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[170,203,1707,1729]" captionTargetBox="[305,1093,562,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-12@2.[305,1093,558,1689]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig.1.Delomerista spp.1–2 —habitus,lateralview:1—D.cf.japonica, female;2 — D.novita,male;3 —D. novita, female, dorsal view of propodeum; 4, 5 — dorsal view of the second metasomal tergite: 4 — D. pfankuchi, male; 5 — D. novita, female; 6–10 — lateral view of ovipositor tip: 6 — D. pfankuchi; 7 — D. borealis; 8 — D. mandibularis; 9 — D.cf. japonica; 10 — D.japonica (non-Carpathian material); 11–12 — lateral view of two basal antennal segments: 11 — D. borealis; 12 — D. mandibularis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454726" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454726/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="28D5C64FFF97FF86B69EFC25A571FBD3" box="[246,260,1009,1035]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">5</emphasis>
); the two basal antennal segments with numerous rows of sensillae (
<figureCitation id="829A06D8FF97FF86B245FC25A01CFBD4" box="[1069,1129,1009,1036]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[170,203,1707,1729]" captionTargetBox="[305,1093,562,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-12@2.[305,1093,558,1689]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig.1.Delomerista spp.1–2 —habitus,lateralview:1—D.cf.japonica, female;2 — D.novita,male;3 —D. novita, female, dorsal view of propodeum; 4, 5 — dorsal view of the second metasomal tergite: 4 — D. pfankuchi, male; 5 — D. novita, female; 6–10 — lateral view of ovipositor tip: 6 — D. pfankuchi; 7 — D. borealis; 8 — D. mandibularis; 9 — D.cf. japonica; 10 — D.japonica (non-Carpathian material); 11–12 — lateral view of two basal antennal segments: 11 — D. borealis; 12 — D. mandibularis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454726" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454726/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="28D5C64FFF97FF86B21FFC25A0E6FBD3" box="[1143,1171,1009,1035]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">11</emphasis>
); the malar space which is about 0.5 × length of basal width of mandible; the black face and upper hind corner of pronotum; the brownish tegulae; the ovipositor which is about 1.8 × length of hind tibia, with simply tapered at apex upper valve (
<figureCitation id="829A06D8FF97FF86B558FB85A719FBB4" box="[816,876,1105,1132]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[170,203,1707,1729]" captionTargetBox="[305,1093,562,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-12@2.[305,1093,558,1689]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig.1.Delomerista spp.1–2 —habitus,lateralview:1—D.cf.japonica, female;2 — D.novita,male;3 —D. novita, female, dorsal view of propodeum; 4, 5 — dorsal view of the second metasomal tergite: 4 — D. pfankuchi, male; 5 — D. novita, female; 6–10 — lateral view of ovipositor tip: 6 — D. pfankuchi; 7 — D. borealis; 8 — D. mandibularis; 9 — D.cf. japonica; 10 — D.japonica (non-Carpathian material); 11–12 — lateral view of two basal antennal segments: 11 — D. borealis; 12 — D. mandibularis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454726" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454726/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="28D5C64FFF97FF86B511FB85A7F2FBB3" box="[889,903,1105,1131]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">7</emphasis>
). Male is distinguisheble by the entirely yellow face and clypeus, the narrow and black malar space (as on 
<figureCitation id="829A06D8FF97FF86B256FBA5A002FB54" box="[1086,1143,1137,1164]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[170,203,1707,1729]" captionTargetBox="[305,1093,562,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-12@2.[305,1093,558,1689]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig.1.Delomerista spp.1–2 —habitus,lateralview:1—D.cf.japonica, female;2 — D.novita,male;3 —D. novita, female, dorsal view of propodeum; 4, 5 — dorsal view of the second metasomal tergite: 4 — D. pfankuchi, male; 5 — D. novita, female; 6–10 — lateral view of ovipositor tip: 6 — D. pfankuchi; 7 — D. borealis; 8 — D. mandibularis; 9 — D.cf. japonica; 10 — D.japonica (non-Carpathian material); 11–12 — lateral view of two basal antennal segments: 11 — D. borealis; 12 — D. mandibularis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454726" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454726/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="829A06D8FF97FF86B2EDFBA5A0E6FB53" box="[1157,1171,1137,1163]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1766,1788]" captionTargetBox="[272,1126,1043,1744]" captionTargetId="figure-372@4.[272,1126,1043,1744]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Perithous spp.: 1 — P. speculator, female, habitus, lateral view; 2 — P. scurra, female, dorsal view of the second metasomal tergite; 3–4 — dorsal view of propodeum and metasomal tergites I–II, female: 3 — P. divinator; 4 — P. septemcinctorius; 5 — P. scurra, male, habitus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454728" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454728/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis id="28D5C64FFF97FF86B2EDFBA5A0E6FB53" box="[1157,1171,1137,1163]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">2</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
), the black tegulae and alongate area superomedia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1A1E1A5DFF97FF86B68BFB65A0D7FAD4" blockId="1.[174,1233,977,1324]" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName id="DDA161DEFF97FF86B702FB65A636FB14" box="[362,579,1201,1228]" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis id="28D5C64FFF97FF86B702FB65A59AFB13" box="[362,495,1201,1227]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">Delomerista</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
look rather like 
<taxonomicName id="DDA161DEFF97FF86B491FB65A72EFB13" box="[761,859,1201,1227]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Scambus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="236" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="28D5C64FFF97FF86B491FB65A72EFB13" box="[761,859,1201,1227]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">Scambus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Ephialtini), but have simple fore tarsal claws (without basal lobe); propodeum with a more-or-less well defined area superomedia; more finely sculptured, matt metasoma; yellow malar space and mandibles (at least basally).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1A1E1A5DFF97FF86B68BFAC5A60FFAF4" blockId="1.[174,1233,977,1324]" box="[227,634,1297,1324]" pageId="1" pageNumber="236">Flight period in Carpathians. May.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
